This article commemorates the 400th anniversary of the first deliberative body in what would become the United States of America, which gathered in Jamestown, Virginia in 1619. The House of Burgesses, now known as the Virginia General Assembly, was formed as a unicameral body of elected individuals who served alongside appointees of the Virginia Company of London. The Burgesses came from diverse backgrounds and were united in their cause for a better future for the settlers and their descendants. The article highlights that the spirit of representative democracy that motivated the statesmen in Jamestown continues to drive the nation forward today. It recognizes the importance of legislative bodies at various levels of government in deliberating and representing the will of the people. The article concludes with a celebration of the blessings of freedom and a prayer for God's blessings on the United States of America.